<body>
  <header role="banner">
    <h1>Bhutanese Textiles: A Living Cultural Legacy</h1>
  </header>

  <main role="main">
    <section>
      <p>
        Bhutanese textiles encapsulate the rich cultural history and spiritual heart of the 
        Himalayan kingdom. More than just woven fabric, these textiles serve as visual narratives—telling 
        stories of Bhutan's beliefs, history, and way of life through delicate craftsmanship and profound 
        symbolism. Weaving in Bhutan is not merely a craft; it is a revered tradition, a way of life that 
        links people to their ancestors and the natural world.
      </p>

      <p>
        At the core of this tradition is <strong>Thagzo</strong>, the art of Bhutanese textile weaving.
         Thagzo reflects Bhutan’s vibrant culture, capturing spiritual beliefs, historical tales, and everyday
          life. The textiles, crafted with techniques passed down through generations, incorporate meaningful 
          symbols such as the dragon (<em>Druk</em>), lotus flowers, and the <em>Tashi Tagye</em>
           (Eight Auspicious Symbols)—all deeply rooted in Bhutanese Buddhism.
      </p>

      <p>
        These textiles are central to religious rituals, festivals, and daily wear.
         Thagzo continues to bridge the past with the present, ensuring that Bhutan’s rich 
         textile tradition remains a vibrant part of its cultural fabric. Beyond their aesthetic 
         value, these textiles act as a visual language, communicating Bhutanese myths, ideologies, 
         and cultural values.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Significance of Bhutanese Textiles</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Spiritual Symbolism:</strong> Patterns often reflect Bhutanese Buddhism. Symbols like the <em>Tashi Tagye</em> embody spiritual enlightenment. The <em>Druk</em>, or Thunder Dragon, is a national emblem symbolizing strength and protection.</li>
        <li><strong>Cultural Narratives:</strong> Designs such as “Pema Lingpa” honor saints and legends, visually preserving Bhutan’s spiritual and historical legacy.</li>
        <li><strong>Social Identity:</strong> Textile patterns and colors denote social rank, with specific designs reserved for royalty, clergy, or commoners.</li>
        <li><strong>Festivals and Rituals:</strong> Traditional garments like the <em>Gho</em> and <em>Kira</em> feature intricate patterns used during important ceremonies and events.</li>
        <li><strong>Women’s Empowerment:</strong> Weaving is a female-led tradition, offering economic freedom and creative expression to Bhutanese women.</li>
        <li><strong>National Identity:</strong> Traditional patterns remind Bhutanese of their heritage and cultural continuity in a modern world.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Appliqué and Embroidery: Expressions of Sacred Art</h2>
      <p>
        Complementing Thagzo are Bhutan’s rich traditions of appliqué and embroidery. 
        Appliqué involves sewing fabric cut-outs onto a base to form vibrant designs,
         often for ceremonial and religious items. Embroidery enhances textiles with hand-stitched
          patterns, adding spiritual symbolism and visual richness.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Royal Textile Academy of Bhutan</h2>
      <p>
        To safeguard this cultural heritage, the <strong>Royal Textile Academy of Bhutan</strong> acts as both a cultural sanctuary and educational hub. Located in the heart of the Himalayas, it preserves traditional textile arts while inspiring new generations. Its galleries and workshops provide a space where Bhutan’s legacy is woven anew through color, pattern, and meaning.
      </p>
    </section>
  </main>

